35.body: Like String, Vec 's are moved, because they don't implement the Copy trait ( see here ). The same move semantics apply. Vectors (and other collections for that matter) are worth talking about because there are so many semantics involved - the container itself, the elements, and the iterators. We use Vec as an example here because it's a very common data structure for collections. Other collections that also don't implement the Copy trait include HashMap and HashSet. Move semantics for arrays, on the other hand, work similarly as structs in that they depend on the type of the item - but that's for another day. Container Items

42.body: Reading elements in a vector via getting the index is tricky. It's just not the same in the programming languages that we know.
42.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Vec<String> ¬ª Items
42.title: Items

43.body:
I mean would you take a look at this! The code below is perfectly fine in the programming languages that I know but here, we get a compiler error saying I cannot move out of index of Vec<String>. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"), String::from("Jane")]; let name: String = names[0]; println!("Hello, {}", name);
} But why? See, if you move only one element out of a Vec, you leave the vector in an invalid state - the vector is not a collection of homogenous elements anymore Implicitly moving out of a Vec is not allowed as it would leave the vector in an invalid state -‚Ääone element is moved out, the others are not (see this StackOverflow post). If I were to iterate this vector, I might access an invalid memory (the element that was moved out) üò±. Thanks for protecting us, Rust. So what do we do?
43.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Vec<String> ¬ª ‚ùå Listing 6-6
43.title: ‚ùå Listing 6-6

44.body:
We can borrow the value that we want by using the indexing operator. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"), String::from("Jane")]; let name: &str = &names[0]; println!("Hello, {}", name);
}
44.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Vec<String> ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 6-7
44.title: ‚úÖ Listing 6-7

45.body:
We can also borrow the value using the .get method. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"), String::from("Jane")]; let name: &str = names.get(0).unwrap(); println!("Hello, {}", name);
}
45.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Vec<String> ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 6-8
45.title: ‚úÖ Listing 6-8

46.body:
We can also borrow the value using the .first() or¬†.last() method (if you want the first and last item, of course). fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"), String::from("Jane")]; let name: &str = names.first().unwrap(); println!("Hello, {}", name);
} But... what if I want to own an element?
46.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Vec<String> ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 6-9
46.title: ‚úÖ Listing 6-9

47.body:
We use the .into_iter() method to own the individual elements. More on iterators in the next chapter. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"), String::from("Jane")]; let mut names_iter = names.into_iter(); let name: String = names_iter.next().unwrap(); println!("Hello, {}", name);
} This example works if you want to own the first element. Afaik, if you want to own the element at index n (for some reason), you would call .skip(n) then call .next().
47.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Vec<String> ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 6-10
47.title: ‚úÖ Listing 6-10

48.body:
For Vec, we can .pop() the last element and own the data. fn main() { let mut names = vec![String::from("John"), String::from("Jane")]; let name: String = names.pop().unwrap(); println!("Hello, {}", name);
}

51.body:
Let's start with a for-loop iterating over names. Why for-loop? We'll get to that. But for now, life's a bed of roses: fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; for name in names { println!("{}", name); }
}
51.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 7-1
51.title: ‚úÖ Listing 7-1

52.body:
Until we add a print statement below the for-loop... where the compiler starts to complain. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; for name in names { println!("{}", name); } println!("Names: {:?}", names);
} Apparently there is an "implicit¬†.into_iter call before the loop." Wait, implicit ? Why?! But okay, let's add that implicit .into_iter:
52.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚ùå Listing 7-2
52.title: ‚ùå Listing 7-2

53.body:
After adding into_iter(), we expect that the program still does not compile. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; for name in names.into_iter() { println!("{}", name); } println!("Names: {:?}", names);
}
53.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚ùå Listing 7-3
53.title: ‚ùå Listing 7-3

54.body:
Hmmmmm let‚Äôs assign a variable to names.into_iter(). So that we can sort of visualise the move. Note that we still expect the program to not compile. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; let names_iter = names.into_iter(); for name in names_iter { println!("{}", name); } println!("Names: {:?}", names);
} What's happening is that using into_iter, we are moving the elements from names into names_iter. As a result, we cannot use names anymore! What do we do?
54.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚ùå Listing 7-4
54.title: ‚ùå Listing 7-4

55.body:
We can borrow elements from names using .iter(): fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; for name in names.iter() { println!("{}", name); } println!("Names: {:?}", names);
}
55.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 7-5
55.title: ‚úÖ Listing 7-5

56.body:
We can use a slice (which implements IntoIterator). fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; for name in &names { println!("{}", name); } println!("Names: {:?}", names);
}
56.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 7-6
56.title: ‚úÖ Listing 7-6

57.body:
If your program allows it, we can switch the code around a bit to borrow names first, then move it: fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; println!("Names: {:?}", names); for name in names { println!("{}", name); }
}
57.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 7-7
57.title: ‚úÖ Listing 7-7

58.body:
We can also clone the vector. Note that there are costs to cloning. fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; for name in names.clone() { println!("{}", name); } println!("Names: {:?}", names);
}
58.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 7-8
58.title: ‚úÖ Listing 7-8

59.body: Using functional programming idioms makes it more obvious that iterators are involved when you want to iterate over elements (especially if you come from programming languages where you don't have to deal with iterators directly). Unlike for-loops, there are no implicit .into_iter() calls. As such, for vectors, we always need to call .iter(), .into_iter(), etc. to get an iterator.

Here it doesn't compile because we need to iterate over the elements, meaning we need get an iterator using, say, .iter(). fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; names.for_each(|name| println!("{}", name)); println!("{:?}", names);
}

60.title: ‚ùå Listing 7-9

61.body:
Here, we use a combination of .iter() and .for_each(). The iterator returns a reference to the elements. We can still use the names object afterward: fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; names .iter() .for_each(|name| println!("{}", name)); println!("{:?}", names);
}
61.breadcrumbs: Move and copy semantics ¬ª Iterator ¬ª ‚úÖ Listing 7-10
61.title: ‚úÖ Listing 7-10

62.body: If you want to move the elements, use .into_iter(). However, note that we can't use the vector afterwards: fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; names .into_iter() .for_each(|name| println!("{}", name)); println!("{:?}", names); }

63.body:
You'll need to redesign your program such that you don't use the moved elements. Here, we moved the print statement in front: fn main() { let names = vec![String::from("John"),String::from("Jane")]; println!("{:?}", names); names .into_iter() .for_each(|name| println!("{}", name));
}
